In article <1993Jun16.185416.29899@fsl.noaa.gov> bear@kestrel.fsl.noaa.gov writes:

>You need a set of one-time pads for _each_ of your correspondents, and
>they likewise.
>
>Assume you need secure communications with 10 people.  You need 10
>_different_ OTPs, and there will be (10 C n) different disks when
>you account for all permutations, where n is the number of people holding
>"conference" conversations.  For n = 2, this is 45 disks for 10 people.
>
>Increase that to 100 people, and you're talking about 4950 disks.

Not necessarily. It is feasible (and a lot more economic) that a number of 
stations share the same pad. Provided no station reuses a part of the pad 
that has already been used there is no weakening in security.

I leave it to one of the many ardent proponents here of OTP to post how this 
can be achieved with certainty. Alternatively, we can all work it our for 
ourselves:-) 

